{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524522"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14005"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14005"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.59,0.08,0.06,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6654"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49637"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6654"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34919"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43459"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49637"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 92-year-old woman presents to the general practitioner with her daughter for her annual health assessment and repeat prescription medications. She has a medical history of glaucoma, type-2 diabetes, hypertension, gout and osteoarthritis. Her medications include perindopril, allopurinol, hydrochlorothiazide, paracetamol SR and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with normal vital signs. Her daughter has noticed multiple lesions on her hands (image) and asks what they are. The patient states they do not cause her any pain and have been there for many years, slowly growing over time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis of these lesions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nodular basal cell carcinoma","Tophus","Synovial cyst","Rheumatoid nodule","Epidermoid cyst"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis image demonstrates a classic \u003Cstrong\u003Etophus\u003C/strong\u003E secondary to uric acid deposition in the setting of this patient\u0027s known history of gout. Tophi are deposits of monosodium urate crystals that typically occur in chronic gout. They are often painless and can grow slowly over time. Tophi are commonly found in the hands, feet, and other areas subject to lower temperatures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENodular basal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a variation of skin cancer and typically presents as a pearly or waxy lump, often with visible blood vessels. It is less likely given this patient\u0027s history and the description/appearance of the lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynovial cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are fluid-filled sacs that develop along the tendons or joints. They are usually associated with joint pain or discomfort, which this patient does not report.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid nodules\u003C/strong\u003E are firm lumps under the skin commonly found in patients with rheumatoid arthritis. They are typically associated with joint deformities and other systemic symptoms, which are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are benign, slow-growing lumps under the skin that can become inflamed or infected. They are usually not associated with a history of gout and are less likely in this context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tophi are deposits of monosodium urate crystals, typically seen in chronic gout.","Tophi can be painless and grow slowly over time.","Tophi are often found in the hands, feet, and other areas subject to lower temperatures."],"references":["Fenando A, Widrich J, Rednam M, Gujarathi R. Gout [Internet]. PubMed. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546606/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34919"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14005"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20916"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20916"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/h44fAQEJp3BKlXmcRHkiAWSPQI4NjF.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/h44fAQEJp3BKlXmcRHkiAWSPQI4NjF.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34919"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-02T14:13:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-02T14:13:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6654"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49637"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedi